<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="48" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,752,2016]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,317,1062,1088]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. This species is distinct from any other one from the Apennines by intervals of elytra with very fine punctuation, the three inner intervals of elytra with stronger lustre and reduced microsculpture (elytra of males with reduced microsculpture throughout), different structures of medial lobe of aedeagus (laterally widest in apical third, dorsally and ventrally with two prominent forward and aside laterodorsal lobes and apex not visible from above; see 
<figureCitation box="[538,619,1217,1243]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 - 6" captionStartId="2.[151,269,1245,1269]" captionTargetBox="[174,1404,191,1244]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,157,1276]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 - 6. Median lobe of aedeagus left lateral view and parameres of Italian Platyderus: Fig. 1. Platyderus casalei sp. n., holotype; Fig. 2. P. magrinii Degiovanni, “ Mte Graeco ”; Fig. 3. P. neapolitanus Chaudoir, “ Emery Napels ”; Fig. 4. P. paganettii sp. n., holotype; Fig. 5. P. vignai sp. n., holotype; Fig. 6. P. vignai sp. n., holotype, parameres." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/190889/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">
Figs. 
<number box="[603,619,1217,1243]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48" value="5.9">5</number>
</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[633,649,1217,1243]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 - 10" captionStartId="3.[151,276,1325,1349]" captionTargetBox="[186,1406,599,1276]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,569,1316]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 7 - 10. Median lobe of aedeagus right lateral view and copulatory piece of Italian Platyderus: Fig. 7. Platyderus casalei sp. n., holotype; Fig. 8. P. paganettii sp. n., holotype; Fig. 9. P. vignai sp. n., holotype; Fig. 10. P. paganettii sp. n., holotype, dorsal and ventral shape of copulatory piece." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/190890/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">9</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[662,736,1217,1243]" captionStart="FIGURES 11 - 18" captionStartId="6.[151,270,1871,1895]" captionTargetBox="[204,1415,214,1837]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,194,1847]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 11 - 18. Median lobe of aedeagus, ventral and dorsal views of Italian Platyderus: Fig. 11. Platyderus casalei sp. n., holotype, ventral view; Fig. 12. P. magrinii Degiovanni, “ Mte Graeco ”, ventral view; Fig. 13. P. neapolitanus Chaudoir, “ Emery Napels ”, ventral view; Fig. 14. P. paganettii sp. n., holotype, ventral view; Fig. 15. P. vignai sp. n., holotype, ventral view; Fig. 16. Platyderus casalei sp. n., holotype, dorsal view; Fig. 17. P. neapolitanus Chaudoir, “ Emery Napels ”, dorsal view; Fig. 18. P. vignai sp. n., holotype, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/190891/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">
<number box="[662,736,1217,1243]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48" value="15.18">15, 18</number>
</figureCitation>
) and the copulatory piece of endophallus.
</paragraph>
